<catsoop-section>Building the Clock Pulse Generator</catsoop-section>

Your seconds counter needs a clock signal to tick automatically. You'll build a 555 timer circuit that generates pulses at approximately 1 Hz (once per second).

### 555 Timer Clock Circuit

```
1. On a separate breadboard area, place the 555 timer IC straddling the center gap.
2. Connect power first:
   - Pin 1 (GND) → ground rail
   - Pin 8 (VCC) → power rail
3. Connect timing components:
   - Pin 7 (Discharge) to one end of a 10kΩ resistor
   - Other end of 10kΩ resistor to VCC
   - Pin 7 also connects to one outer pin of the 1MΩ potentiometer
   - Middle pin (wiper) of potentiometer to pins 2 and 6 (connect these together)
   - Pins 2 and 6 also connect to positive leg of 10µF capacitor
   - Negative leg of 10µF capacitor to GND
4. Connect control pins:
   - Pin 4 (Reset) → VCC (keeps timer enabled)
   - Pin 5 (Control Voltage) → 0.01µF capacitor → GND
5. Connect output:
   - Pin 3 (Output) → pin 1 (Clock) of seconds units digit CD4026
```

